---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SEO from '../components/SEO.astro';
import { t } from '../lib/ui';

const LOCALE = 'en' as const;
---

<BaseLayout lang={LOCALE}>
  <SEO
    slot="head"
    title={`${t(LOCALE, 'about.title')} — Eduardo Kohn`}
    description="Eduardo Kohn — software engineer (10+ yrs) turned independent researcher, working from computer-networking foundations toward cyber-physical systems (CPS/ICS) security."
    canonicalPath="/about"
    jsonLd={{ kind: 'about' }}
  />
  <article class="u-container page">
    <h1 class="page-title">{t(LOCALE, 'about.title')}</h1>
    <p>
      I'm Eduardo Kohn, a software engineer with more than ten years building full-stack systems — Java/Spring Boot and
      Elixir/Phoenix on the backend, React and TypeScript on the frontend, React Native on mobile, with PostgreSQL,
      Docker, and Kubernetes in production. I'm now in a deliberate transition from engineering practice toward applied
      research in
      <strong>cyber-physical systems (CPS)</strong> and <strong>industrial control systems (ICS/OT) security</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>
      My approach is bottom-up. Before the security layer, I'm rebuilding rigorous foundations in computer networking —
      TCP/IP, routing, DNS, and the protocol internals that real systems actually depend on — working through Kurose
      &amp; Ross and validating the theory against packet captures rather than taking it on faith. I've always been more
      interested in understanding <em>why</em> things work than in shipping features — from the bytes on the wire to the cryptography
      that secures a protocol.
    </p>
    <p>
      Within security, the direction that most motivates me is <strong>Cyber-Physical Systems</strong>: the intersection
      of computing, networking, and physical processes that underlies critical infrastructure like power grids,
      industrial control systems, medical devices, IoT, and autonomous vehicles. When a vulnerability crosses from the
      digital into the physical, the consequences stop being abstract — and that technical responsibility is exactly
      what draws me in.
    </p>
    <p>
      I'm an active contributor to the Erlang/Elixir ecosystem. I have four merged pull requests in the <a
        href="https://github.com/phoenixframework/phoenix"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer">Phoenix framework</a
      > — query-string encoding, code generation, installer crash handling, and documentation fixes, reviewed by core maintainers
      — along with open contributions to Cowboy and its supporting libraries, from TCP socket teardown to SWAR-based HTTP/1
      parsing. Working on open source at that scale has been my main engineering school: it's where I've learned in practice
      what it takes to design concurrent, fault-tolerant systems on serious theoretical foundations — OTP, supervision trees,
      message passing.
    </p>
    <p>
      This blog is where I think in public, writing as I work through each topic. <a href="/papers">Papers</a> are longer
      pieces written with scientific rigour — abstracts, citations, theorems, proofs; my DNS study, from concept to packet,
      lives there. <a href="/posts">Posts</a> are shorter notes that share an idea before it is finished enough to formalise.
    </p>
    <p>
      Professionally, I've worked with frontend and cross-platform mobile (React Native, iOS and Android) since 2016 and
      as a full-stack engineer since 2021, across companies including EY, AB InBev, Leroy Merlin, and Capgemini. I'm
      pursuing a Bachelor's in Computer Science (Universidade São Judas Tadeu, 2024–2028) and, now based in Ohio,
      engaging with US-based researchers as I prepare to apply for doctoral work in applied security.
    </p>
    <p>
      Find me on <a href="https://github.com/eagle-head" target="_blank" rel="me noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a>,
      <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/eduardokohn84" target="_blank" rel="me noopener noreferrer">LinkedIn</a>, or
      subscribe to the <a href="/newsletter">newsletter</a> to get new pieces by email.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page {
    --measure: var(--measure-paper);
    padding-block: var(--space-6);
  }
  .page-title {
    font-size: var(--text-2xl);
    font-weight: var(--font-weight-extrabold);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-tight);
    line-height: var(--leading-tight);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-5) 0;
    color: var(--color-fg);
  }
  .page p {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    color: var(--color-text);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-4) 0;
  }
</style>
